segments.text: Certainly, here's the translation of the Hebrew text into English.
Normally, she woke up with the birds chirping.
They had an agreement of sorts to check who chirps first.
They, of course, but in any case, she always rose early in the morning.
This time she slept deeply and her eyes opened only around seven.
She jumped out of bed, stepped into the shower, returned to her shorts and grandpa tank top.
Intending to tend a little to the garden and iron the uniform, she'd washed and hung to dry yesterday.

Barefoot, her hair down to dry from washing, she stepped onto the large porch overlooking the garden, turned on the sprinklers in one part of the garden and started weeding in the other, seeing how the violets had multiplied since last week and her heart rejoiced.
For several years now, she had a strong feeling that Lucy was watching from above.
Seeing how she cared for her garden and when the garden blossomed, both were happy.
She cleaned the porch, returned the chairs to their place, went to turn on the sprinklers on the other side of the garden.
then cleaned her feet and crossed the dining room to the back area facing the rooms.
The garden there was small and narrow, surrounding only the entrance path, but along its length, flowers and silver baskets were planted on both sides of the entrance path.
She knelt, cleaned, raked, and delighted in the colors around her.
When she was busy like that, the thoughts wondering what would happen were pushed aside.
In a busy daily schedule, there's no time for reflection.
She wiped her forehead with her arm, pushed her loose hair back from her face, and suddenly heard his voice behind her.
Now I understand you're also responsible for the blooming around here.
My God!
How could this be?
She had completely forgotten he had stayed here for the night.
In full daylight, the situation seemed somewhat surreal to her.
She looked at him with great embarrassment, stood up slowly, brushing off her knees from the sand stuck to them.
Turned on the tap, washed her hands, wiped them on the back of her pants and cleaned her feet with the rag at the entrance.
Come in.
I'll make you breakfast and you can head home.
He followed her into the kitchen.
Drying the dishes from yesterday made him feel at home.
She handed him two plates and cutlery, and he went to set the table.
He placed two glasses from the shelf, opened the fridge, took out the orange juice, and put it on the table as well.
Then he returned to her, received from her a basket of sliced bread, butter, and yellow cheese, and while he placed everything on the table, she walked in with the omelets she had prepared.
And so as if it was their daily routine, they sat down to eat breakfast together,
Speaking little, but feeling a friendly ease.
As they were almost done eating, he looked directly at her.
Look, I have a wild idea, but please take it at face value.
He paused for a moment, then said very seriously.
I would like you to join me for the weekend with my family.
It's a warm and spacious home, and I think you deserve a bit of rest.
There's also a beach nearby, and I believe you could really enjoy it.
My parents are warm and pleasant people, and they would be very glad to meet you.
For a moment, she gasped, not knowing how to react.
It really came out of nowhere.
In her embarrassment, she mumbled as an excuse that she hadn't managed to iron the uniform on the clothesline.
He laughed.
Take them as they are, he said.
I promise you we have an iron at home.
Come on, he urged her.
When was the last time you left the place, not for the military?
You've already cleaned and tidied.
Even took care of the garden, and there's nobody left here for the weekend.
After a long moment of silence, she lifted her eyes to him, meeting the warmth in his and heard herself answering him.
I can't believe I'm saying this, but okay, give me 15 minutes to get ready.
Go ahead," he replied to her.
I'll finish my things in the meantime.
Only when she was in her room did she ask herself what was happening here.

She put on her long jeans with the simple t-shirt from yesterday, packed the shorts into a bag, added a sleeveless button-down shirt, slipped on clogs, and put her only pair of flats and the unironed uniform in her bag.
She also stuffed in a toothbrush and a sleep shirt, and there she was, ready to go.
She head into the kitchen and found him there, finishing drying the clean dishes, placing them on the nearby shelf, feeling very comfortable in her kitchen.
That's it, I'm finished.
He said, so am I, she replied.
I'll just lock up, then we'll head out.
By the time she shuttered the blinds and locked the front door, he had already collected his things from the room and was waiting for her by the jeep.
Want a drive?
He asked with a teasing smile.
She realized he had heard her conversation with the doctor.
No thanks.
It was a one-time thing.
A matter of life and death, she smiled at him.
So they had a shared secret without even mentioning it.
The drive was pleasant.
The radio played familiar tunes and she hummed along to some.
Sometimes he joined in with the words.
She couldn't remember the last time she had felt so at ease and relaxed.
He was right.
She deserved a break.
As if intentionally, she filled her days with endless activity, so her mind wouldn't dwell on the issues at hand.
She had made a big decision for her, and yet she discovered every day that she could handle it.
I have a surprise for you.
He said suddenly, but I won't tell you until we get there.
She was curious and glanced at him sideways.
How did the serious stern commander who rarely spoke become nearly a friend in the last 24 hours?
He caught her glance and returned one of his own.
You'll have to explain a few things to me.
Well, maybe half-two isn't exactly the right word.
But in your own time, when you feel like you can, I'd love to hear.
She put on a slightly embarrassed smile.
Knowing exactly what he meant, without realizing it, they found themselves on the outskirts of Batey and I. He navigated the jeep to a part of the settlement away from the other houses.
From afar, almost at the edge of the cliff overlooking the sea, she saw a not too large house surrounded by trees.
Is this your home?
She marveled.
Yes, it's our little piece of heaven.
He stopped the Jeep at the entrance, and within a moment, his mother burst out the door and ran toward him.
With a brown Labrador dog bounding behind her, he got out of the vehicle, embraced his mother lovingly, and patted the dog's back, which jumped up to his chest.
And soon his father stood next to him, and they exchanged a hug accompanied by backpats.
His mother was small, with a cropped haircut, and appeared young for her age, whereas his father was tall like him, and his hair was curly and thick.
They resembled each other very much, those two, except that the father's hair was already streaked with gray.
She slowly got out of the jeep, smiling at them with embarrassment.
Welcome, his mother greeted her, and immediately hugged her, as did his father.
Their warmth melted her and overcame her embarrassment.
The dog too was already by her side, rubbing against her leg, and she crouched down next to it and petted and hugged it.
She understood that Dan must have used the phone in the pink house's lobby to inform them she was coming.
He took her bag with his from the back seat, not allowing her to carry anything.
When they entered together into his home, she saw a charming house, simple, pleasant, not ostentatious, but embracing like them.
Wonderful paintings hung on the walls, warm-toned rugs spread on the floor, and a large wooden library was filled with books up to the ceiling.
Then,
A bit to the right of the library, she saw a grand piano, though old but beautiful.
She gasped, feeling Dan watching her eyes, not taking his offer.
That's the surprise, he said.
I knew it would make you happy.
Do you play, his mother Naomi asked.
Well, not really, she answered slightly stammering.
Just for myself, by ear.
But I really love it.
He led her to his sister's room, who had been studying in London for two years.
The room was spacious and pleasant, with two photographs of her on the wall.
She looked like her mother, small and delicate, with light hair and big eyes.
She studies dance, he noted, placing her bag on the bed.
Come, I'll show you the way down to the sea.
Along the entire length of the house was a large covered porch.
Beautiful wicker furniture stood around a heavy wooden table that looked handcrafted.
Under the porch lay the sea.
As if the porch overlooked the entire cliff.
What a wonderful place and what a stunning view, she admired.
This house is something special.
It opens the heart.
He looked at her for a moment with an unreadable expression.
Your house is special too.
He walked with her to the other side of the house.
From afar she saw the stable and the heads of the horses peeking over the wooden gate.
She forgot herself a little and his presence and approached the horses quickly, petting the head of one and then the other, hugging its neck.
The horse brought its head close to her and she giggled with joy.
You're sweet, she told it.
If you behave well, maybe I'll take you for a ride on the beach.
There was something in this creature that instantly created a connection with her.
Almost mystical.
Dan stood aside, watching her caress the horses, whispering to them.
Do you want to go for a ride a little?
He asked.
Yes.
Yes.
Certainly.
She lifted her head to him in surprise.
He opened the stable gate and handed her a bridle to put on the horse.
No, I'm not good at this," she said.
I prefer to ride bareback.
I'll manage with its mane.
He looked at her amazed, she constantly surprised him.
He prepared his saddle and bridle, and by the time he tied them on, she was already lightly on her horse, holding the mane and gently stroking its neck.
Follow me," he said to her.
The descent from the cliff is a bit steep, and you need to be careful.
Slowly and carefully they made their way towards the beach, strolling calmly side by side, with the waves almost lapping at the horse's feet.
Wow, she thought to herself, what happiness!
She was aware of the smile spread across her lips.
Suddenly, she clicked her tongue, lightly kicked her bare feet at the horse's sides, and it broke into a light gallop.
The wind blew in her face, and she held the mane tightly.
Dan recovered from the surprise and began to gallop after her until they stopped near a large rock across the beach.
They laughed aloud.
A free, joyful laugh.
I don't remember when I enjoyed it so much.
She said in a somewhat bashful tone.
What luck I didn't refuse your offer.
Thank you so much.
His expression changed.
I'm glad you didn't refuse either, he said quietly.
On their way back, he informed her they had guests for dinner, friends of his parents visiting from abroad, each from a different country.
No need to worry, he added.
They are very nice.
You probably already understand, even without me explaining too much, that I'm not afraid of strangers.
That's how I grew up, and that's what I know.
I love people.
Good, he said.
You'll have some time to rest.
And I'm already telling you, there's no need to dress up.
Just like you're used to.
Simple and comfortable.
Well, okay, he laughed.
Maybe put on shoes.
Dinner at seven.
They returned the horses to the stable, brought them water buckets, and then she headed to the house, to her room.
He stayed behind to arrange the bales of hay.
The house was very quiet.
His parents were nowhere to be seen.
She walked through the kitchen, bent her head over the sink to drink water straight from the tap, then passed through the living room on her way to her room.
Her eyes fell on the piano.
and she couldn't resist it.
She sat down in front of it, gently listed the black cover and opened it.
A piece of green felt was laid on the keys.
She folded it carefully, placed her fingers on the cold keys, and let the music guide her, completely forgetting herself, playing softly the man I love by Gershwin.
One day he'll come, a man I love, and he'll be big and strong, the man I love, and I'll try my best to make him stay.
Dan stopped in his tracks, careful not to interrupt.
He watched her completely absorbed, playing with full intention, aware of the emotional release it provided her.
He stood hidden at the corner of the hallway, leaning on the door frame, watching her intently and understanding that despite everything, her secrets were kept with her.
And still, he couldn't quite decipher her.
A great sadness enveloped her, and every moment he discovered another layer, yet so much was hidden rather than revealed.
She finished playing, took a deep breath, closed her eyes for a moment, then returned the felt strip to its place, carefully closed the piano, stood up and went to her room.
She went into the shower, let herself enjoy the running water, washed the scent of the horses from her hair, and clean, smelling good, she lay down in bed under the blanket.
She closed her eyes, feeling sleep wrapping around her and sank into it with quiet delight.
In the evening, her eyes opened as if she'd set an alarm.
She put on the sleeveless button-down shirt, her only pair of jeans, the one she wore during the traumatic event with the rusty man and the black flats.
After that, she braided her hair and placed the braid on her right shoulder, then went from her ring through the living room to the large dining area next to it.
Mother Naomi was already bustling around, setting the table.
Can I help?
She asked, I'm really good at this.
Gladly, Naomi answered and handed her fabric napkins and silverware.
In no time, Leora took over the dining table as if she were at her small hotel.

She arranged the napkins in a festive fold, placed the silverware according to the rules, grabbed the wine glasses, polished them with a kitchen towel, and set them to the right of the tall beverage glasses.
She didn't notice that Mother Naomi stopped her tasks and stared at her in amazement.

After finishing, she went out to the garden, picked some of the orange nasturtium flowers blooming along the path, trimmed the stems, filled two wine goblets with them, and placed them on either side of the table.
The table looked like a picture that was a shame to alter, Mother Naomi thought.
Who is this girl?
Where did he find her?
Lyora raised her eyes to Naomi with a childlike Victoria's smile.
Pretty?"
she asked.
You must be joking, right?
It's simply lovely.
Thank you so much.
Can I help with something in the kitchen?
Leora asked.
No, thanks, dear.
You've done more than enough.
By the way, don't think I didn't hear you playing the piano earlier.
It was wonderful.
I'll want to hear more later.
Leora smiled to herself.
She felt comfortable in this house.
She'd forgotten how heavy her solitude could sometimes be.
Dan and his father arrived and admired the beautifully set table.
It wasn't me.
It was the work of the young lady, proclaimed Mother Naomi.
Perhaps we should have a drink before the guests arrive.
Father David asked.
And while he went to pour, she moved slightly to a nook between the dining area and the living room to make room.
And there, suddenly, a large oil painting caught her eye, causing her to freeze in place.
A farmer stands in the middle of a plowed field, raising a hoe.
His muscled arms are prominent.
Every muscle vividly drawn.
She felt the air leave her lungs.
Her breath was taken away.
Without realizing it, Dan suddenly stood very close, very close, looking at her with concern.
Are you feeling okay?
Did something happen?
She lifted her eyes to him and he met her blue eyes shifting to dark indigo, a bit gloomy.
Where did you get that painting?
She asked in a defiant, almost angry tone.
I really don't know.
I think my mom received it from someone.
He looked at her with tuzzlement, trying to understand why she was upset.
Never mind, she said, not quite controlling her voice.
It's one of the things I'll need to explain.
She forced herself to recover, took deep breaths and approached to receive her glass of wine.
She took a long sip, feeling the wine wash down her body, calming, strengthening, bringing the air back to her lungs.
She was conscious of Dan's scrutinizing gazes and felt that even Mother Naomi occasionally stared at her.
They wished to understand her, and it was understandable, but the time hadn't come yet.
The day after tomorrow, they'd return to the base, and everything would return to normal.
Meanwhile, as if she entered a fairy tale, and for a short while, allowed herself some rest.
Outside, a car was heard stopping.
And they went out to receive the guests.
After warm handshakes, they all walked in and introduced each other.
She barely held back from saying, hey, I know you.
Keeping it to herself.
They switched to English.
Father David introduced them to her.
It's an honor, she said to one, an enchante in French to the other, even though he was introduced to her in English.
Immediately after, she said in Hebrew, nice to meet you.
Remembering that the French ambassador knew Hebrew and had been greatly praised for it.
Mother Naomi looked at her in astonishment, and she hurried to explain.
I remember they were the ambassadors of the United States and France until a few good years ago.
Everyone smiled with satisfaction.
Only Mother Naomi was a bit stunned by the lady.
the meal flowed amiably.
Naomi turned out to be a wonderful cook, and Leora naturally assisted her from the start.
Serve, clear the table after each course.
Without noticing, they became a skilled team.
Afterward, they poured tea and coffee and cut from the cake, and everyone settled comfortably, after two bottles of wine on the couches.
Occasionally, she entered conversations in English naturally and directly, sometimes seasoning it with a word here, a word there, in French.
Dan sat beside her, not moving away, feeling a kind of pride, oddly mixed with a sense that he must protect her.
But from what?

At some point, when they switched to talking about Naomi's love for art, the former French ambassador noted that only because he knew it was a good house, he agreed to part with his beloved oil painting before returning to France.
I bought it a few years ago from the painter, who's also the owner of a charming small hotel in Ashkelon, the Pink House.
a very unique person.
I loved coming there from time to time and got friendly with the couple who owned it.
Even sent wall there, he said.
Dan was in shock.
Now he understood what happened to her in front of the painting.
It's a painting by her father.
Now he also understood that all the paintings hanging on the walls of the pink house were hers too.
He looked at her overwhelmed, finding her returning an emotional gaze.
Suddenly, she gathered courage, raised her head, looked directly at the ambassador, and said in French, quietly, almost whispering.
This is a painting by my father.
I'm the little girl from the pink house.
Silence descended instantly.
The Frenchman rose silently.
She too slowly got up, and he hugged her at length.
I was so sorry to hear about your mother," he said in Hebrew with his charming accent.
She was an exceptional woman, learned to speak French from a book I brought her.
I'm so sorry," he said again.
Before sitting down, he turned back to English and addressed the American who looked on in bewilderment.
You won't believe who this girl is.
Do you remember the first time you came to the pink house and the barefoot girl who showed you the way?
Only forgetting to mention it was also her home?
Oh my God!
reacted the American.
It can't be.
You were about nine.
The last time I was with you, your mom was still with us.
A wonderful woman.
A true lady.
And your father.
What a character.
She said nothing, feeling overwhelmed by her thoughts and memories.
And without being able to stop them, she was thrown back to that day when the American ambassador searched for her home secluded in his luxurious car.
A long, luxurious vehicle, the kind not seen in the area, stopped beside her and from window peered a chubby man with a round, smiling face.
He addressed her in English and asked, do you happen to know where the pink house is of
Of course," she replied, just around the corner, on your right hand side, you'll see the sign.
She didn't think back then that she needed to mention it was her home.
He thanked her, his moon-faced smiling, and she thought to herself he was a nice man.
About twenty minutes later she walked into the dining room, a tanned and barefoot girl in a white tank top and shorts with elastic at the edges.
Kim, a beautiful Irish setter with long, reddish fur and communicative eyes, used to sleep in her room at the foot of her bed and followed her everywhere, trailing behind her even now.
The chubby man with the moon face and his entourage were already seated at a table, laden with all sorts of good food, and Lucy and Joseph stood beside them.
He smiled at her with a big grin.
Here is our beautiful guide again," he said, then asked.
How come you speak such good English?
And she, with the seriousness and innocence of a nine-year-old girl, answered.
I think I'm just intelligent."
A big laugh came from everyone present.
Lucy and Joseph laughed with them, and the nice man said to her, You definitely are.
This story was recounted for years after, and now it was again brought back to her, and the memories stirred her soul.
She remained standing, moved that they knew of her mother's passing three years ago, moved that they remembered her at all.
Mother Naomi and Father David did not take their eyes off her.
Bander stood she had been through tough days, that she grew up in a very special home, and that the painting Father Dan loved so much was painted by her father.
What a small world.
Dan stood beside her and placed a hand on her shoulder.
She did not resist.
It wasn't a hug, just a warm touch from a hand saying, I'm here, seeking to calm this charged and emotional moment for her.
The smile returned to her lips and overwhelmed with excitement, mixed with embarrassment.
She said, The main thing is that the painting found a good home.
Thank you so much for your kind words about my mother.
I never imagined you knew she had passed away.
It touches my heart deeply.
She thanked them again.
Then sat back down on the couch, Dan beside her.
Everyone resumed their seats as if getting an approval and the conversation flowed leisurely once more.
At the end, I never quite understood how you knew English so well.
The former American ambassador suddenly said, she smiled in embarrassment.
A few years before you came to us, 10 oil drillers from Texas came to establish the first oil drill in the country around Helets in the south.
And this group lived at the pink house for almost two years, she explained.
They arrived one morning when I was just a little over five.
She began to tell.
And without noticing, continued to recount how in the late morning hours of that day, a small bus stopped by the house.
From it stepped out one after another those Texan oil drillers, dressed in what Lucy would call good shirts.
But the first thing she saw, mainly because she was still short and low, were their boots.
Never before had she seen such shoes.
They also made some noise when they walked.
Beautiful boots with colorful decorations and magnificent embossments that reached up to their ankles with their jeans tucked into them, and they all spoke English.
From that moment on, and for about two years, only English was spoken in that house.
At first, she didn't quite understand and would run to Joseph or Lucy for explanations.
But slowly, she began to understand more and more.
Children learn quickly, Lucy would say.
They had charming names.
There was George McCleary, who was a bit square in shape with broad shoulders.
And Stephen Franklin, who was tall with tangled dark hair.
And Billy Austin, who was very tanned.
And Lucy said he was probably mixed with something.
And John Willis, who had eyeglasses with a big number like a magnifying glass.
And there was Frank Humphrey, of course.
Lucy said he was as handsome as a movie star.
He was thin and tall, his wavy hair light.
And his blue eyes looked at you over sculpted cheekbones.
Sort of a Paul Newman.
Frank Humphrey was a gentle soul.
He loved to talk for hours with Lucy.
Mainly he talked, and she.
Listened.
He missed home, Lucy once said to Joseph.
That's why he told so many stories.
They would go to work early in the morning, not before eating breakfast that wouldn't shame any lunch.
Sausages with eggs and often even potatoes.
Finally, they'd finish with pancakes, on which they poured maple syrup.
In the mid-1950s, there wasn't such food in the country.
To feed 10 hungry oil drillers, you needed Moishe.
Moishe would bring boxes full from the American Embassy in Tel Aviv, with all the suitable products, including steaks, lots of steaks, and Coca-Cola, which came and concentrate in large cans.
Joseph would pour a little at the bottom of the glass and add soda from a glass siphon, and that's how they would drink.
This was perhaps the first place in the country where you could drink Coca-Cola.
But mostly, beer flowed there, full crates of a beer beer, in the evenings.
When they returned to the hotel, they were already starving and just wanted to sit down to eat, but Lucy wouldn't let them.
First, you have to wash, and by the time you're done, the food will already be ready, she said, holding them tight, as Joseph would say with a smile.
And indeed, they would return half an hour later, clean, polished, their hair still damp.
The steaks with potatoes and a beer beer were laid on the table, and the dining room looked like a pub in the Wild West.
After dinner, they would proceed to the bar with whiskey on the rocks, and many times would get completely drunk, falling asleep on the table, sometimes on the grass outside.
But by morning, as if nothing happened, showing up in their work clothes for that breakfast, which wouldn't shame any lunch, finishing it all, grabbing their helmets, waving goodbye, and setting off.
You'd kill me if I understood where all that food went.
Lucy would say every time to Joseph.
On September 23, 1955, the miracle happened.
Finally, real oil erupted from the helets field.
All the steves and billies and Franks returned from a day's work.
Their faces and clothes still washed in black oil with smiles stretching from ear to ear on their faces.
They took off their shoes at the entrance and said to Lucy, nothing doing.
We're not washing.
First, let's eat and toast.
Celebrate this joy with all the oil on us.
She gave in, of course.
Prepared delicious dishes for them, and Joseph served them drinks without end.
That night turned into a real feast, lasting till dawn.
The next day's paper headline announced, Oil Flows and Hellets.
And their picture, the drillers bathed in spurting oil, appeared prominently too.
A year later, in October 1956, the Sinai War broke out, and overnight they gathered up their belongings, left some behind.
kissed and hugged everyone and flew back to faraway Texas.
She was not yet seven then, but the English lingered in her memory.
That's how I was able to direct you in English to my pink house.
They all left in a single day, she continued to tell, except for Jerry Wolf, who arrived before them and left after them.
He had no connection to them, and he wasn't afraid of wars because he was a pirate.
But that belongs to another story, she said, a big and childish smile on her face.
Suddenly, she fell silent.

Realizing she had completely let herself go while reminiscing those enchanting days of her childhood, she felt so embarrassed in front of Naomi and David and no less so in front of Dan, feeling as if she had shamed him.
She raised her eyes with a sheepish expression, but to her amazement found everyone so cheerful and happy from her story that she calmed down.
A little later, the guests left, not before sending their regards to Joseph and wishing her success in whatever she undertakes.
Almost without exchanging a word, she busied herself tidying up the kitchen with Mother Naomi.
The men tidied up the dining ring and went out to the porch with a drink in hand.
She turned to Naomi, asking permission to wash the dishes.
I need this.
It soothes me."
Are you sure, Naomi asked?
Yes, go to sleep.
I'll finish and head to bed too.
Just please tell me where the iron is.
So I can iron the uniforms.
Tomorrow, half an hour later, when most of the dishes were clean and laid on towels she spread on the counter, Dan showed up at the kitchen entrance, grabbed a towel and began drying the dishes.
I need to maintain my expertise," he laughed.
Something warm and freed very much was between them, like being old friends.
But there still were secrets that needed telling.
At every moment another new piece was revealed to him, he thought.
This girl went through a lot in her life, standing impressively bravely with whatever daily life brought.
He thought about how independent she was, riding horses like she was born on them, playing the piano without sheets just by ear.

speaking good English and quite decent French, knowing how to conduct a conversation on almost any subject, and yes, knowing to drink wine and pour it professionally into glasses without a drop spilling.
All of this gradually became charming in his eyes, wrapped in simplicity, three of all pose,
She radiated quiet confidence and a lot of courage.
A lot of courage.
And oh, he smiled to himself.
How could he forget she's a champ at washing dishes and cleaning rooms?
Such a collection of talents packed into 48 kilograms, with 40 of them being her eyes.
He gazed deeply into them, smiling gently.
Then said, that's enough for today.
Go to sleep.
Tomorrow is another day.
Leora fell asleep in an instant, drained from all the day had brought to her soul, sleeping deeply.
Early in the morning, with the birds chirping, she opened her eyes.

She lazily got out of bed, washed her face, tied her hair and barefoot in her shorts and grandpa's tank top, went to the kitchen, boiled water for coffee, and took her coffee cup to the back room where the ironing board with the iron stood.
She leisurely ironed her uniform.
then slipped her ranks onto the epaulettes.
Only after finishing did she notice Dan's uniform also waiting in the basket nearby.
Without a second thought, she handled those two and hung them on the hanger.
Only then did she go to the porch, from there carefully down to the beach.
Without realizing, Brandy the dog joined her, sticking to her legs and darting back and forth.
She wandered leisurely, collecting shells, drawing with her foot in the sand, stepping into the shallow waters up to her ankles, and coming back out.
tossing a stick for the dog who brought it back with excitement.
A sense of complete freedom washed over her.
It had been a long time since she felt unburdened by tasks.
She knew she'd taken on too much, but she also knew no other choice was available.
And ultimately, it wasn't particularly hard for her.
She was already used to it.
She just knew it wasn't completely normal for a girl her age to be raising herself for almost two years now.
Supporting herself and hiding from the outside world her struggles and dilemmas.
What could she tell him?
What did she want to reveal and what not?
He was patient.
A secret keeper type.
Not much of a talker.
She already figured that out.
Some things he already understood on his own.
She was so glad he brought her to rest.
This place was one of the most magical she had known.
Her father had been a military attach in several countries, and they stayed there for a few years in his childhood.
His English was more fluent than hers.
She had acquired hers by listening to those Texan oil drillers during their stay at the hotel.
In the kitchen, Mother Lucy spoke with Fortuna in French.
That's how she acquired her languages, which improved during her high school studies.
When they returned from the last mission, they looked for a place to build their home.
Someone sold them the plot quite cheaply because it was remote and on the cliff.
They didn't understand that this was its uniqueness.
So he, like her, grew up in great freedom with animals and by the sea.
And he, like her, serious and responsible with a touch of humor sneaking in now and then.
How did it happen that in less than two days together, an inexplicable closeness developed between them, from almost strangers to very close friends?
She felt the warmth he radiated when talking to her or looking at her, not knowing how to interpret it, but understood that starting.
Tomorrow they would have to be careful not to reveal it.
